Spent a bit of time to configure my Nokia mobile to teethering wih my Linux and T-Mobile. Here is some steps that may help the others :
If you don&rsquo;t have that blue bluetooth led switched on on your Dell Latitude D630 Laptop you have to enable it. I haven&rsquo;t find any way to do that via the Linux Kernel module but with Windows under Vmware Player (3.0) enabling Bluetooth and installing the driver (manually not via the setup.exe) enabled bluetooth. Switched on bluetooth on the Phone and attached to the laptop via gnome bluetooth applet thingy. Get my phone device number from hcitool scan. And did this (as root) : cat &lt;/etc/bluetooth/rfcomm.conf
# RFCOMM configuration file.
rfcomm0 {
# Automatically bind the device at startup
bind yes;
# Bluetooth address of the device
device YOUR:PHONE:DEVICE:NUMBER;
# RFCOMM channel for the connection
channel 4;
# Description of the connection
comment &ldquo;Nokia N95&rdquo;;
}
EOF
/etc/init.d/bluetooth restart
cat &lt;/etc/ppp/chat-tmobile
ABORT BUSY
ABORT &lsquo;NO CARRIER&rsquo;
ABORT &lsquo;NO ANSWER&rsquo;
ABORT ERROR
REPORT CONNECT
SAY &lsquo;Calling t-mobile&hellip;\n&rsquo;
&quot;&quot; &lsquo;ATZ&rsquo;
OK &lsquo;ATE0V1&amp;D2&amp;C1S0=0+IFC=2,2&rsquo;
SAY &lsquo;Modem reset.\n&rsquo;
SAY &lsquo;Setting APN&hellip;&rsquo;
OK &lsquo;AT+cgdcont=1,&ldquo;IP&rdquo;,&ldquo;general.t-mobile.uk&rdquo;&rsquo;
SAY &lsquo;APN set\n&rsquo;
SAY &lsquo;Dialling&hellip;\n&rsquo;
OK &lsquo;ATDT*99#&rsquo;
TIMEOUT 30
CONNECT &quot;&quot;
EOF
cat &lt;/etc/ppp/peers/t-mobile
/dev/rfcomm0
460800
idle 7200
modem
noauth
lock
crtscts
defaultroute
user &ldquo;user&rdquo;
password &ldquo;pass&rdquo;
noipdefault
usepeerdns
updetach
noccp
nobsdcomp
#novj
ipcp-restart 10
ipcp-accept-local
ipcp-accept-remote
lcp-echo-interval 65535
lcp-echo-failure 10
lcp-max-configure 10
connect &ldquo;/usr/sbin/chat -v -f /etc/ppp/chat-tmobile&rdquo;
EOF
Under Debian distros you can enable the connection with the command &lsquo;pon t-mobile&rsquo; or you for the others can do via the manual way with the command &lsquo;pppd call t-mobile&rsquo;.

If you want to generate properly encrypted password to feed to chpasswd, the most easier and proper way is to do that from command line :
[code lang=&ldquo;bash&rdquo;]
echo &ldquo;encryptedpassword&rdquo;|openssl passwd -1 -stdin
[/code]
If you want to generate in pure python you can do it like that :
[code lang=&ldquo;python&rdquo;]
def md5crypt(password, salt, magic=&rsquo;$1$&rsquo;):
import md5
m = md5.new()
m.update(password + magic + salt)
# /* Then just as many characters of the MD5(pw,salt,pw) */
mixin = md5.md5(password + salt + password).digest()
for i in range(0, len(password)):
m.update(mixin[i % 16])
# /* Then something really weird&hellip; */
# Also really broken, as far as I can tell. -m
i = len(password)
while i:
if i &amp; 1:
m.update(&lsquo;x00&rsquo;)
else:
m.update(password[0])
i &raquo;= 1
final = m.digest()
# /* and now, just to make sure things don&rsquo;t run too fast */
for i in range(1000):
m2 = md5.md5()
if i &amp; 1:
m2.update(password)
else:
m2.update(final)
if i % 3:
m2.update(salt)
if i % 7:
m2.update(password)
if i &amp; 1:
m2.update(final)
else:
m2.update(password)
final = m2.digest()
# This is the bit that uses to64() in the original code.
itoa64 = &lsquo;./0123456789ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz&rsquo;
rearranged = &rsquo;&rsquo;
for a, b, c in ((0, 6, 12), (1, 7, 13), (2, 8, 14), (3, 9, 15), (4, 10, 5)):
v = ord(final[a]) &lt; &lt; 16 | ord(final[b]) &laquo; 8 | ord(final[c]) for i in range(4): rearranged += itoa64[v &amp; 0x3f]; v &raquo;= 6
v = ord(final[11])
for i in range(2):
rearranged += itoa64[v &amp; 0x3f]; v &raquo;= 6
return magic + salt + &lsquo;$&rsquo; + rearranged
[/code]
You need to feed it up with a salt, like this :
[code lang=&ldquo;python&rdquo;]
def generate_salt(count):
import random, string
char = string.ascii_letters + string.digits + string.punctuation.replace(&rsquo;:&rsquo;, &lsquo;&rsquo;)
return string.join(map(lambda x,v=char: random.choice(v), range(count)), &lsquo;&rsquo;)
[/code]

If you like me you have a big screen with your laptop and wants to automate when your X session start to get the best resolution, you can use that script :
[code lang=&ldquo;bash&rdquo;]
#!/bin/bash
function get_resolutions() {
xrandr|while read -a line;do
RES=&quot;${line[1]}x${line[3]} &quot;
[[ ${RES} != [0-9]* ]] &amp;&amp; continue
echo ${RES}
done
}
_BEST_RES=0
BEST_RES=
for res in $(get_resolutions);do
_res=${res/x/}
[[ $_res -ge ${_BEST_RES} ]] &amp;&amp; {
BEST_RES=${res}
_BEST_RES=${_res}
}
done
xrandr -s ${BEST_RES}
[/code]

If you like me, you have to do a lot of installs1 of the same test machine with the same IP and have to ssh it you will notice this annoying message :
IT IS POSSIBLE THAT SOMEONE IS DOING SOMETHING NASTY! Someone could be eavesdropping on you right now (man-in-the-middle attack)! It is also possible that the RSA host key has just been changed. The fingerprint for the RSA key sent by the remote host is 54:9d:c0:37:3a:80:48:6c:82:ec:d1:84:93:61:24. Please contact your system administrator. Add correct host key in /home/cboudjnah/.ssh/known_hosts to get rid of this message. Offending key in /home/cboudjnah/.ssh/known_hosts:595 Password authentication is disabled to avoid man-in-the-middle attacks. Keyboard-interactive authentication is disabled to avoid man-in-the-middle attacks. Agent forwarding is disabled to avoid man-in-the-middle attacks. I have automated the cleanup by a script :
[code lang=&ldquo;bash&rdquo;]
#!/bin/bash
H=$1
[[ -z ${H} ]] &amp;&amp; { echo &ldquo;Need a host as argument&rdquo;; exit 1 ;}
LINE=$(ssh -o StrictHostKeyChecking=yes $1 &rsquo;exit&rsquo; 2&gt;&amp;1 | sed -n &lsquo;/Offending key/ { s/.*://;s/r//;p }&rsquo;)
[[ -z ${LINE} ]] &amp;&amp; { echo &ldquo;Nothing to clean&rdquo;; exit; }
sed -i -n &ldquo;$LINE!p&rdquo; ~/.ssh/known_hosts[/code]
1 Like having to tests bunch of FAI.

If you want to emulate Control-L in Eshell (the Emacs Shell) like in Xterm, you can use this :
(defun eshell-show-minimum-output () (interactive) (goto-char (eshell-beginning-of-output)) (set-window-start (selected-window) (save-excursion (goto-char (point-max)) (line-beginning-position))) (eshell-end-of-output)) And add a key bind to it in your custom hook :
(local-set-key &#34;\C-l&#34; &#39;eshell-show-minimum-output)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;

When i have a password comparaison function using crypt(3) i really should remember that the comparaison stop at the 7 bytes, because that stuff is weird for me :
In 1: import crypt
In [2]: seed=&lsquo;foo!bar&rsquo;
In [3]: crypt.crypt(&lsquo;abcdefghaa123456681&rsquo;, seed)
Out[3]: &lsquo;foEoVhbk7ad7A&rsquo;
In [4]: crypt.crypt(&lsquo;abcdefghpax;lalx;al&rsquo;, seed)
Out[4]: &lsquo;foEoVhbk7ad7A&rsquo;
In [5]:
any stuff after the 6 char will always get ignored by the hash algorithm.
